1
00:00:56,700 --> 00:00:59,080
Good evening everyone, good evening, of course, to those who have come and have indeed come,

2
00:00:59,080 --> 00:01:03,599
to those who are here tonight in large numbers, in this beautiful Maurice Fleuret space,

3
00:01:03,599 --> 00:01:07,559
at the National Conservatory of Music and Dance of Paris.

4
00:01:07,559 --> 00:01:11,800
Tonight, it is the Department of Early Music, led by Pascal Bertin,

5
00:01:11,800 --> 00:01:16,160
and also the Vocal Disciplines, led by Jean-Marc Demeuret,

6
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:17,879
that are being showcased.

7
00:01:17,879 --> 00:01:20,919
A few words specifically about the Department of Early Music.

8
00:01:20,919 --> 00:01:25,199
It is a department that benefits, of course, from the extreme quality of its professors,

9
00:01:25,199 --> 00:01:29,000
who are all musicians recognized on the international stage.

10
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,400
Moreover, each season, specific projects, like tonight,

11
00:01:33,400 --> 00:01:36,519
involve prestigious guests.

12
00:01:36,519 --> 00:01:41,760
Also noteworthy, the students have access to a magnificent collection of instruments.

13
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:45,080
What's also interesting in the philosophy of this department,

14
00:01:45,080 --> 00:01:50,160
is the way it's never disconnected from the historical continuity.

15
00:01:50,160 --> 00:01:54,199
I mean, this work on ancient instruments is constantly linked

16
00:01:54,199 --> 00:01:56,639
with a reality that comes later in time.

17
00:01:56,639 --> 00:02:00,879
Baroque is put into perspective, along with what is called the classical period

18
00:02:00,879 --> 00:02:02,599
or the pre-romantic period.

19
00:02:02,599 --> 00:02:05,279
Of course, this is the spirit of this program.

20
00:02:05,279 --> 00:02:09,360
Tonight, this will also be the focus of my first question to our esteemed guest,

21
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:12,559
the violinist and conductor Sigiswald Kuijken.

22
00:02:12,559 --> 00:02:16,639
Later, we will discuss other topics, more related to staging

23
00:02:16,639 --> 00:02:21,240
with Marie Kuijken, after the Mozart Symphony that opens our program

24
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:26,440
and just before the Intermezzo by Haydn, 'La Canterina,' which will close it.

25
00:02:26,440 --> 00:02:29,119
So, my first question to Sigiswald Kuijken.

26
00:02:29,119 --> 00:02:34,039
Why have you chosen, in conjunction with Haydn's Intermezzo,

27
00:02:34,039 --> 00:02:38,119
this early Symphony by Mozart, which is certainly not one of his most famous

28
00:02:38,119 --> 00:02:38,919
or most played pieces?

29
00:02:38,919 --> 00:02:42,880
It's a symphony from 1773.

30
00:02:42,880 --> 00:02:44,479
Mozart was 17 years old.

31
00:02:44,479 --> 00:02:48,759
He was still in Salzburg, but he had already traveled, notably to Italy.

32
00:02:48,759 --> 00:02:51,199
Perhaps this is already a first clue to the explanation.

33
00:02:51,199 --> 00:02:56,399
I think Mozart was a very likeable young man when he was 17 years old.

34
00:02:56,399 --> 00:03:04,520
Somewhat ahead of his time, he had already been influenced by many sources.

35
00:03:04,520 --> 00:03:08,440
The first was his father, of course, who was not a great composer,

36
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:10,240
but who was a skilled tradesman.

37
00:03:10,240 --> 00:03:13,360
After his travels, he benefited greatly.

38
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:18,639
He was accepted into the Academy in Bologna when he was around 14-15 years old,

39
00:03:18,639 --> 00:03:21,320
which was quite exceptional.

40
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:25,759
So, this symphony, it's already composed by someone who knows his craft.

41
00:03:25,759 --> 00:03:28,639
Why did I choose this symphony and not another?

42
00:03:28,639 --> 00:03:33,119
Because, as you know, there are 41 symphonies by Mozart, right?

43
00:03:33,119 --> 00:03:36,559
It's because I wanted a piece with flutes.

44
00:03:36,559 --> 00:03:38,320
And you might ask why.

45
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:39,960
That's the pragmatism of musicians.

46
00:03:39,960 --> 00:03:43,479
Indeed, and I believe it's necessary to think this way.

47
00:03:43,479 --> 00:03:50,279
Because in 'La Canterina', which is, let's say, the main piece of our evening,

48
00:03:50,279 --> 00:03:54,839
there are two flutists who play only in the first number.

49
00:03:54,839 --> 00:03:58,199
After that, in those times, they were expected to,

50
00:03:58,199 --> 00:04:01,559
switch to oboe and even the English horn.

51
00:04:01,559 --> 00:04:05,279
Now, it's not like that anymore, flutists no longer play the oboe.

52
00:04:05,279 --> 00:04:10,199
So, the two flutists who play in the Haydn,

53
00:04:10,199 --> 00:04:13,080
I preferred that they play something else as well.

54
00:04:13,080 --> 00:04:17,359
So I found a Mozart symphony where there are flutes instead of oboes.

55
00:04:17,359 --> 00:04:18,720
There aren't many of those.

56
00:04:18,720 --> 00:04:22,799
And it gives a completely natural, completely different color.

57
00:04:22,799 --> 00:04:27,160
It's in G major, but here the flute parts are placed, let's say,

58
00:04:27,160 --> 00:04:30,920
a fifth higher than the normal oboe parts.

59
00:04:30,920 --> 00:04:34,119
And that creates a different sonic spectrum.

60
00:04:34,119 --> 00:04:36,079
And I believe that's the only reason.

61
00:04:36,079 --> 00:04:37,600
And it's a very lovely symphony.

62
00:04:37,600 --> 00:04:40,959
So there's no hesitation.

63
00:04:40,959 --> 00:04:43,320
When you, like you have been for years, delve into the repertoire of what's broadly known as ancient music,

64
00:04:43,320 --> 00:04:46,079
you realize that many musicians like you encroach upon the classical and even romantic territories.

65
00:04:46,079 --> 00:04:48,559
But how far can we go with this?

66
00:04:48,559 --> 00:04:51,320
With this concept of historically informed music,

67
00:04:51,320 --> 00:04:53,000
can we go almost up to our times?

68
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,760
To push it to the absurd, we could go up to last night.

69
00:04:55,760 --> 00:05:02,640
One could even imagine playing Pierre Boulez's 'Le Marteau sans maître'

70
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:06,519
on an ancient instrument from the 1950s, right?

71
00:05:06,519 --> 00:05:10,880
There, we're pushing into the absurd, and I myself am convinced,

72
00:05:10,880 --> 00:05:17,760
personally, I do not say that everyone will think like me,

73
00:05:17,760 --> 00:05:20,799
that the further we advance in the history of music,

74
00:05:20,799 --> 00:05:25,880
the less the use of so-called "correct" instruments

75
00:05:25,880 --> 00:05:28,359
is really an absolute condition.

76
00:05:28,359 --> 00:05:30,600
I think one should view this from a distance

77
00:05:30,600 --> 00:05:32,760
and with a certain humor as well.

78
00:05:32,760 --> 00:05:37,559
I believe what's important is not to mix up the big picture,

79
00:05:37,559 --> 00:05:43,959
I mean, the instruments used before the French Revolution.

80
00:05:43,959 --> 00:05:46,000
It's something different than after,

81
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,640
but it's mainly the mentality of the musicians that has changed.

82
00:05:49,640 --> 00:05:52,359
The Revolution was something significant.

83
00:05:52,359 --> 00:05:57,519
Maybe one day, we will... I don't know.

84
00:05:57,519 --> 00:05:59,440
But it's something very strong

85
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:02,959
and thus the mentality of the instrumentalist changes

86
00:06:02,959 --> 00:06:06,799
and also the instruments, the preferences for certain sounds,

87
00:06:06,799 --> 00:06:10,320
the virtuosity, the overflowing expression, and all that,

88
00:06:10,320 --> 00:06:13,600
it's typically post-Revolution.

89
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:18,720
Before, composers and musicians were more like craftsmen,

90
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:21,200
tradespeople.

91
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:24,440
Haydn had the rank of a valet at Esterházy.

92
00:06:24,440 --> 00:06:25,600
– Even though he was Kapellmeister.

93
00:06:25,600 --> 00:06:29,239
– Yes, but he never complained about it.

94
00:06:29,239 --> 00:06:31,160
It's inscribed in another world.

95
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:35,200
Musicians were employees of this Mr. Kapellmeister

96
00:06:35,200 --> 00:06:38,040
and of Prince Esterházy.

97
00:06:38,040 --> 00:06:39,679
And that's normal.

98
00:06:39,679 --> 00:06:46,160
So, we have a different education when we start from that place.

99
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:47,920
If later, we are children of the Revolution,

100
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:52,320
we will do individualistic things and will not let ourselves be dominated.

101
00:06:52,320 --> 00:06:54,359
– A final question, Sigiswald.

102
00:06:54,359 --> 00:06:55,959
We often use the term classical.

103
00:06:55,959 --> 00:06:57,519
Classical music, for the general public,

104
00:06:57,519 --> 00:07:03,320
encompasses all music from practically Monteverdi up to today.

105
00:07:03,320 --> 00:07:06,119
The classical style, according to Charles Rosen, is much more specific.

106
00:07:06,119 --> 00:07:11,720
It defines an era, a style, and even certain musical tools, compositionally speaking.

107
00:07:11,720 --> 00:07:15,359
So, regarding this Mozart symphony we're about to hear,

108
00:07:15,359 --> 00:07:17,119
we hear a sonata form in the first movement.

109
00:07:17,119 --> 00:07:19,440
That's quite characteristic.

110
00:07:19,440 --> 00:07:22,239
But in the last movement, there's a fugato.

111
00:07:22,239 --> 00:07:24,679
This will come back later, as we well know, in Mozart's music.

112
00:07:24,679 --> 00:07:26,600
But is this a remnant of the past, this fugato?

113
00:07:26,600 --> 00:07:29,399
– I think it's both a remnant and also a sign of Mozart's curiosity,

114
00:07:29,399 --> 00:07:32,399
who, being a member of the Academy in Bologna,

115
00:07:32,399 --> 00:07:35,559
among other things, had to demonstrate that he was proficient in counterpoint,

116
00:07:35,559 --> 00:07:40,480
fugatos, things that were not really the language of the time in terms of gallantry,

117
00:07:40,480 --> 00:07:45,839
but they were part of the past.

118
00:07:45,839 --> 00:07:49,799
So, he proved that he mastered them, and increasingly afterwards,

119
00:07:49,799 --> 00:07:56,959
in the quartet, you will see that he is very strong in that area.

120
00:07:56,959 --> 00:08:00,320
And Beethoven, as well as Haydn – And then there will be Baron van Swieten, but that's another story.

121
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:00,839
– Exactly.

122
00:08:00,839 --> 00:08:02,600
– We'll let you return to your instrument

123
00:08:02,600 --> 00:08:05,160
and the musicians will take the stage

124
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:07,480
for Mozart's Symphony No. 27 in G Major,

125
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:10,000
K.199, of course,

126
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:13,720
performed by the ensemble of the Paris Conservatory under the direction of Sigiswald Kuijken.

127
00:25:25,280 --> 00:25:28,280
So, Marie Kuijken, good evening.

128
00:25:28,280 --> 00:25:34,280
We're going back a few years compared to this Mozart Symphony.

129
00:25:34,280 --> 00:25:37,280
'La Canterina' is an intermezzo in music.

130
00:25:37,280 --> 00:25:38,280
What exactly is an intermezzo?

131
00:25:38,280 --> 00:25:44,280
Is it a kind of interlude intended to be inserted between two acts of a more serious opera?

132
00:25:44,280 --> 00:25:47,280
Yes, initially that's how it was.

133
00:25:47,280 --> 00:25:52,280
It's a form that originated in the first half of the 18th century.

134
00:25:52,280 --> 00:26:02,280
In this idea, characters from the serious opera would take a more comedic pause.

135
00:26:02,280 --> 00:26:06,280
In the second half, it evolved.

136
00:26:06,280 --> 00:26:13,280
It's interesting to see that Haydn, on his manuscript, wrote "Interlude,"

137
00:26:13,280 --> 00:26:17,280
but on the libretto, it's written "Opera buffa."

138
00:26:17,280 --> 00:26:24,280
The two forms were already starting to blend and influence each other.

139
00:26:24,280 --> 00:26:33,280
We're in 1766, the time when Haydn was appointed Kapellmeister at the Esterházy court.

140
00:26:33,280 --> 00:26:38,280
What do we know today about the context, the way it was created there?

141
00:26:38,280 --> 00:26:41,280
Do we have any documents? Do we know how it was staged?

142
00:26:41,280 --> 00:26:46,280
Yes, there aren't specific documents about this opera,

143
00:26:46,280 --> 00:26:53,280
but there are many general theatrical sources from that period that can be read and studied.

144
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:56,280
Some are quite general, others are very specific

145
00:26:56,280 --> 00:27:00,280
and show exactly the rules of how one was supposed to behave on stage

146
00:27:00,280 --> 00:27:02,280
and what was done and what was not.

147
00:27:02,280 --> 00:27:04,280
It wasn't like today; it wasn't rigid.

148
00:27:04,280 --> 00:27:07,280
There are two important aspects.

149
00:27:07,280 --> 00:27:17,280
One is the visual aspect, which aimed to create as if there was always a living painting.

150
00:27:17,280 --> 00:27:26,280
How to say? If at the opera you could do a freeze-frame, the action should always look beautiful.

151
00:27:26,280 --> 00:27:30,280
And this is one aspect, so in the rules of how to carry oneself,

152
00:27:30,280 --> 00:27:33,280
that we weren't slouching, for instance.

153
00:27:33,280 --> 00:27:37,280
It was an offense to the king who might be in the audience listening

154
00:27:37,280 --> 00:27:41,280
and who himself also had an education in how to comport and all that.

155
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:44,280
The king danced, etc.

156
00:27:44,280 --> 00:27:50,280
Another important aspect is verisimilitude.

157
00:27:50,280 --> 00:27:57,280
It means that the ideal, obviously these are ideals we try to reach,

158
00:27:57,280 --> 00:28:02,280
we never completely achieve them, that's for sure.

159
00:28:02,280 --> 00:28:07,280
But verisimilitude means that the action should appear real.

160
00:28:07,280 --> 00:28:11,280
It isn't, obviously, because they are actors, they are singer-actors.

161
00:28:11,280 --> 00:28:14,280
But how to make it seem real?

162
00:28:14,280 --> 00:28:19,280
In the 18th century, they were well aware of how we function.

163
00:28:19,280 --> 00:28:25,280
That is, if someone has a thought or a feeling, hears something, sees something, it starts there.

164
00:28:25,280 --> 00:28:28,280
First, there's a reaction in the heart, in the eyes, in the face,

165
00:28:28,280 --> 00:28:34,280
about what they think, what's happening, or the emotion that's coming.

166
00:28:34,280 --> 00:28:40,280
First the eyes, which are the mirror of the soul.

167
00:28:40,280 --> 00:28:43,280
From the eyes and face, it moves to the body, which makes a gesture

168
00:28:43,280 --> 00:28:51,280
or moves or something like that.

169
00:28:51,280 --> 00:28:57,280
And only after that, it goes into the voice, into the words, or into the singing.

170
00:28:57,280 --> 00:29:01,280
And if we respect this, it was really in the sources,

171
00:29:01,280 --> 00:29:03,280
we find a lot about this aspect.

172
00:29:03,280 --> 00:29:09,280
If we respect this, we are good actors and the action will appear believable.

173
00:29:09,280 --> 00:29:12,280
And then it's something very joyful because there's also parody involved.

174
00:29:12,280 --> 00:29:18,280
Absolutely, yes. In fact, a major part of the comedic aspect of this opera

175
00:29:18,280 --> 00:29:21,280
is the parody of the "opera seria."

176
00:29:21,280 --> 00:29:26,280
In fact, the opera seria was more static,

177
00:29:26,280 --> 00:29:31,280
had more grand and more pathetic gestures, we would say today.

178
00:29:31,280 --> 00:29:38,280
And the comic opera, the opera buffa, was livelier, faster,

179
00:29:38,280 --> 00:29:41,280
and could mock the opera seria a bit.

180
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:44,280
That was an aspect that was done quite a lot.

181
00:29:44,280 --> 00:29:47,280
Thank you for this staging and for these words just before,

182
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:53,280
so 'La Canterina' an intermezzo in music with Victoria Jung in the role of the singer,

183
00:29:53,280 --> 00:29:58,280
Gasparina, Sahy Ratianarinaivo as the singing teacher Don Pelagio,

184
00:29:58,280 --> 00:30:02,280
Makéda Monenet as the supposed mother Apollonia

185
00:30:02,280 --> 00:30:05,280
and Juan Medina in the role of the merchant's son,

186
00:30:05,280 --> 00:30:08,280
Don Ettore, and of course the ensemble of the Paris Conservatory,

187
00:30:08,280 --> 00:30:13,280
conducted by Sigiswald Kuijken and staged by Marie Kuijken.

